english:
  title: 'Ascending Three Peaks: Remembering Old Friends in the Capital'
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Sitting in stillness, distant thoughts arise—
    I climb to the summit of Three Peaks.
    Gazing northwest toward Song Mountain,
    High and noble, dark clouds drift and gather.

    Old friends dwell in that region below,
    Chasing each other through day and night in play.
    But a bird enters the clouds and vanishes,
    And my thoughts drift on, endless and long.

    I gather wild herbs, yet they don't fill my palm,
    So I scatter them along the roadside.
    To go back would not be difficult—
    Yet why do I linger here so long?

    The palaces hold their pleasures, it's true,
    And yet the mountains' solitude calls to me.
    With a great song I grasp the cassia boughs,
    And spend my days in idle wandering free.
  footnotes:
    - Song Mountain (松山) refers to Songak, an alternative name for the mountains near Kaesong, which served as the capital before Seoul became the main royal center.
    - The three peaks may refer to a specific mountain or range near Kaesong visible from a particular vantage point, likely associated with the poet's memories of that region.
    - The cassia tree (桂) is a traditional symbol in East Asian poetry representing immortality and the celestial realm, here used to express the poet's aspirations amid his contemplation of distance from friends.
